<para id="fs-idm41104416">(a)<newline/><media id="fs-idm63850832" alt="A Lewis structure shows two oxygen atoms double bonded together, and each has two lone pairs of electrons.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="CNX_Chem_07_03_Question7a_img.jpg"/>
</media><newline/>
In this case, the Lewis structure is inadequate to depict the fact that experimental studies have shown two unpaired electrons in each oxygen molecule.<newline/>
(b)<newline/><media id="fs-idm76406432" alt="A Lewis structure shows a carbon atom that is single bonded to two hydrogen atoms and double bonded to an oxygen atom. The oxygen atom has two lone pairs of electrons.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="CNX_Chem_07_03_Question7b_img.jpg"/>
</media><newline/>
(c)<newline/><media id="fs-idp37290624" alt="A Lewis structure shows an arsenic atom single bonded to three fluorine atoms. Each fluorine atom has a lone pair of electrons.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="CNX_Chem_07_03_Question7c_img.jpg"/>
</media><newline/>
(d)<newline/><media id="fs-idm29017600" alt="A Lewis structure shows a nitrogen atom with a lone pair of electrons single bonded to a chlorine atom that has three lone pairs of electrons. The nitrogen is also double bonded to an oxygen which has two lone pairs of electrons.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="CNX_Chem_07_03_Question7d_img.jpg"/>
</media><newline/>
(e)<newline/><media id="fs-idm67346912" alt="A Lewis structure shows a silicon atom that is single bonded to four chlorine atoms. Each chlorine atom has three lone pairs of electrons.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="CNX_Chem_07_03_Question7e_img.jpg"/>
</media><newline/>
(f)<newline/><media id="fs-idm62683280" alt="A Lewis structure shows an oxygen atom with a lone pair of electrons single bonded to three hydrogen atoms. The structure is surrounded by brackets with a superscripted positive sign.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="CNX_Chem_07_03_Question7f_img.jpg"/>
</media><newline/>
(g)<newline/><media id="fs-idm804688" alt="A Lewis structure shows a nitrogen atom single bonded to four hydrogen atoms. The structure is surrounded by brackets with a superscripted positive sign.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="CNX_Chem_07_03_Question7g_img.jpg"/>
</media><newline/>
(h)<newline/><media id="fs-idp792848" alt="A Lewis structure shows a boron atom single bonded to four fluorine atoms. Each fluorine atom has three lone pairs of electrons. The structure is surrounded by brackets with a superscripted negative sign.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="CNX_Chem_07_03_Question7h_img.jpg"/>
</media><newline/>
(i)<newline/><media id="fs-idp7083808" alt="A Lewis structure shows two carbon atoms that are triple bonded together. Each carbon is also single bonded to a hydrogen atom.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="CNX_Chem_07_03_Question7i_img.jpg"/>
</media><newline/>
